<TITLE> 15pc rise for social sectors </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 10 (bdnews24.com) -- The new budget for 2010-11 financial year unveiled on Thursday proposed allocation of Tk 194.97 billion, or 14.8 percent of the total budget amount, for poverty reduction and social safety sector. Together, the two sectors will cover programmes for food assistance, employment of the ultra poor, livelihood improvement of people in the char (shoal) area and allowance for old-age people. Finance minister Abul Maal Abdul Muhith unveiled the Tk 1321.7 billion budget, which accounts for 16.9 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP), in the parliament. The minister proposed allocation of Tk 57.26 billion for food safety programmes, including low-price open market sale of food items, food for works, vulnerable group feeding, vulnerable group development, test relief, gratuitous relief, and food assistance for Chittagong Hill Tracts people. He also proposed Tk 35.46 billion for livelihood improvement and poverty reduction projects for char people, Tk 1.4 billion for employment of the rural poor in road repair projects, and Tk 684.5 million for employment of people affected by Monga (starvation like situation) in the country's northern region. The budget proposed allocation of Tk 10 billion for employment projects that would solely target .7 million ultra poor across the country. The minister said in his budget speech that 0.6 million ultra poor of 16 districts had benefited from same projects, implemented at a cost of Tk 11.76 billion, in the current financial year. An amount of Tk 8.91 billion was proposed for allowance of the old-age people, whose number will be increased by 225,000 to 2.47 million next fiscal year, Tk 1.03 billion for allowance of 286,000 poor disabled people, and Tk 333.2 million for upabritti (stipend) for disabled students. The minister proposed Tk 2.91 billion for improvement of maternal health and nutrition, Tk 732 million for maternity allowance for poor mothers, and Tk 3.31 billion for allowance for distressed widowed and divorcee women, and Tk 731.3 million for street children and orphans. The budget projected a GDP growth of 6.7 percent for the new fiscal year, as against 5.5 percent for the current year. 
